name: Women Techmakers Frankfurt - Opening Talk
description:
</a>

As a part of the Women Techmakers powered by the Google Developer Group we are opening our chapter in the Rhein Main Region.

Our goal is to connect, share experiences, learn and improve together.

Join us at the opening event with wine, snacks and interesting talks from inspiring women in tech to celebrate the start of the program in Frankfurt.

Agenda:

18:30 Drinks & Snacks: Doors open

19:00 Welcome/Our story (Anja Schumann and Olga Kostova, Women Techmakers)

Anja established WTM in <a href="https://www.meetup.com/de-DE/womentechmakershamburg/">Hamburg. She is currently working as a Business IT Consultant in Frankfurt and happy to be back in the Rhein Main Region that reminds her of her life as a student in Marburg. She has a passion for entrepreneurship and also launched her own app business to the app store this year. Before that she was transforming business processes in E-Commerce and Supply Chain Management for companies like Tchibo and Lenovo.

Olga is a Digital Data Analyst. She is currently consulting a German Company in Hamburg but constantly traveling the world. Anja and Olga met at one of the Meetups in Hamburg.

19:20 Welcome from Rest of the Google Developer Group Frankfurt (GDG Frankfurt)

19:30 Interview with a Woman in Tech: Christa Koenen, CEO DB Systel

20:00 *Break*

20:15 Women in Tech/ Nicole Göbel, Director Travel & Transportation Accenture & Theresa Bihn Java Software Engineer and Tech Lead

Theresa is an Agilist, a Solution Designer and a Software Engineer (Java). She works since nearly 6 years for Accenture as an IT-Consultant and helps her clients to build innovative, sustainable software. Theresa wrote her first program when she was 15 years old and is ever since convinced that only a diverse group of software engineers can build innovative software that truly solve the customer’s problems.
Theresa was keynote speaker at the WJAX 2015, wrote an article for informatik-aktuell, gave several interviews, won the Panda Women Leadership Contest in 2014, and supports students in their last school year to gain their first IT-Project experience by building mobile apps since 5 years.

Theresa’s vision is to become a role-model for women and girls who want to start their career in tech.

Nicole Göbel is a managing director at Accenture, a global consultancy and professional services company with over[masked] employees in more than 120 countries. Here she focuses on the travel and transportation industry. Nicole holds a degree in tourism economics with majors in computer sciences and marketing and has more than 20 years of experience in project work within the industry e.g. at airlines, tour operators and railways, always at the cross-roads of functional departments and IT.

20:45 Networking and Drinks

22:00 Closing

Women Techmakers is Google’s brand and global program for women in technology. Women Techmakers provides visibility, community, and resources for women in technology to drive innovation and participation in the field. Women Techmakers events are designed to promote an environment of inclusivity for women in technology, as well as celebrate women leading the industry. We want to advance, grow and celebrate women developers, designers, and technology entrepreneurs.

name: Digital Transformation
description:
Every business is a digital business

Digital transformation is the reinvention of an organization through the use of digital technology to improve the way it performs and serves its constituents. Digital refers to the use of technology that generates, stores and processes data.

The term transformation refers to a fundamental change to an organization's day-to-day business from the types of products and services it produces to how it delivers them. Simply implementing technology alone doesn't bring about digital transformation but changing an organization to reap the potential of those technologies does. 

In spite of all the benefits, digital transformation is a struggle for many organizations and there is no one blueprint for success

This meetup is about... understanding the hype behind 'Digital Transformation'. Our speakers will give us some insights what happens on the road to digital transformation.

Agenda: 

• 18:30 Doors open (Room Jupiter): Snacks & Drinks

• 19:00 Welcome (WTM Frankfurt)

• 19:05 Digital Transformation @Cofinpro (Cofinpro)

• 19:25 Digital transformation vs "Innovation Theater" -
what we learned at KfW (Jure Zakotnik & Ingmar Müller, Digital Office KfW)

• 19:45 Break - time to refill your drinks

• 20:00 Digital Transformation @DB Systel (Claudia Stützel, CIO DB Systel)

• 20:25 The challenge of Change (Michael Beckmann) 

• 20:45 Snacks & Discuss

name: Choosing your first Frontend Javascript framework
description:
Everyone has differing opinions on which Frontend framework is “best”, which one is easiest to pick up, and which one is most sought after in the industry. Is it React? Ember? Polymer? Vue? Well, we won’t answer that question for you, but we do promise to shed some light on a few of the most popular frameworks today, dive into the code, and help inspire you to try something new and find your own preference.

This workshop is best-suited for those with some basic knowledge of Javascript. We also ask that you bring along your own laptop (with an editor installed and node) to the event so you can write some code along with us. We have limited space for this event, and would like to give preference to women - so ladies make sure you sign up soon!

Please use this link to secure your spot at the event, and tell us which framework interests you most: https://goo.gl/forms/yKLmjitPyEuwJMHE2

The event will start at 6:30pm, with snacks and drinks provided courtesy of Record Evolution. Looking forward to seeing you there!

Agenda:

6:30pm - Doors open (Help yourself to snacks and drinks!)

6:45pm - Intro from WTM

7:00pm - Interactive Demos (React, Vue.js and Polymer)

8:30pm - Open Discussion / Comparisons / Q&A

name: Learn to Read Microexpressions
description:
Learning how to decode the face is like having a super power.

The face is the window into the soul–if you know how to read it. The good news is we can already tell a lot about someone by their face. That sounds like the popular series 'Lie to me'? Knowing how to read and interpret microexpressions is an essential part of understanding nonverbal behavior and reading people. Susanne Primbs is our special guest and will tell you everything you need to know about microexpressions

Agenda:

18:30 Doors open - Networking

19:00 Welcome!

19:15 Microexpressionen - Susanne Primbs
(Program Manager HR Enterprise Standards for Europe & Russia CIS)

20:00 Open Discussion about Microexpressions

20:30 Networking

Google IWD'18

Google strives to cultivate a wholly inclusive workplace around the globe. A key component of that vision is empowering women to pursue their dreams and build tools that change the world.

Having a diversity of perspectives and ideas leads to better decision-making, more relevant products, and makes the industry much more interesting. We believe that by creating the right environments, programs and policies, women in tech are better positioned to drive transformational change in the industry and beyond.

name: DACHFest 2018
description: THE HUMAN SIDE OF TECH DACHFest is a two-day conference focused on making a difference. Discover all the different ways in which emerging technology is transforming lives, find out how to make your apps and websites friendly towards everyone, learn the secrets of building and nurturing a diverse community — let our speakers surprise and inspire you! And don't forget to make new friends: there will be plenty of opportunities to meet people passionate about your favorite things. Join us and get your ticket here (deals, discounts and scholarships available): https://dachfest.com/ For the community, by the community DACHFest is a part of the global DevFest series of events, and it is organized by tech communities — Google Developer Groups and Women Techmakers chapters — from not just one, but three different countries: Germany, Austria, and Switzerland. Joining forces has enabled us to build a conference the way we have always wanted to: non-profit and volunteer-run, friendly towards everyone, committed to diversity and inclusion, and making a real impact.

description:
Digitization will significantly change our work processes and the way we work. Change is coming; the only question is what will change, and how quickly. Second, we will see the emergence of new forms of collaboration that are more digital, mobile, efficient and connected.
